entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued February 6 at 4:02PM AKST by NWS Fairbanks AK
entry.summary:
A strong storm will move north over the Eastern Bering Sea today through Thursday. This low is expected to bring strong southerly gales, along with snow and blowing snow to the West Coast from the Yukon Delta to the Bering Strait through Thursday.
Winds gusting to 60 mph and periods of blizzard conditions and freezing rain or sleet are expected over the Yukon Delta and St Lawrence Island with this storm from this afternoon through Thursday. Winds gusting 40 to 50 mph and blowing snow with periods of low visibility are expected this evening into Thursday for inland sections of the Yukon Delta, along the Norton Sound Coast, and in the Bering Strait.
The strong winds will cause sea levels to rise 2 to 3 feet above normal today from the Bering Strait south Wednesday through Thursday. This could cause water to seep up onto the ice along the coast on Wednesday into Thursday. No flooding is expected, but this could affect the trails that cross river ice and sea ice near the coast from the Bering Strait south.
entry.cap:areaDesc: Shishmaref; Bering Strait Coast; Southern Seward Peninsula Coast; Interior Seward Peninsula; Eastern Norton Sound and Nulato Hills; Yukon Delta Coast; Lower Yukon River; St Lawrence Island

A strong storm will move north over the Eastern Bering Sea today through Thursday. This low is expected to bring strong southerly gales, along with snow and blowing snow to the West Coast from the Yukon Delta to the Bering Strait starting on tonight and continuing into Thursday.
Winds gusting to 60 mph and periods of blizzard conditions and freezing rain or sleet are expected over the Yukon Delta and St Lawrence Island with this storm from this afternoon through Thursday. Winds gusting 40 to 50 mph and blowing snow with periods of low visibility are expected this evening into Thursday for inland sections of the Yukon Delta, along the Norton Sound Coast, and in the Bering Strait.
Southerly gales developing tonight over the Eastern Bering Sea will continue through Wednesday night. This will bring water levels up 2 to 3 feet from the Bering Strait south Wednesday through Thursday, which could cause water to seep up onto the ice along the coast on Wednesday into Thursday. No flooding is expected, but this could affect the trails that cross ice near the coast from the Bering Strait south.

entry.title: Avalanche Warning issued February 6 at 4:32AM MST by NWS Great Falls MT
entry.summary:
AVWTFX
THE FOLLOWING MESSAGE IS TRANSMITTED AT THE REQUEST OF THE GALLATIN NATIONAL FOREST AVALANCHE CENTER.
ISSUED ON February 06 2024 AT 04:23 am
AVALANCHE WARNING
The Gallatin National Forest Avalanche Center is continuing a Backcountry Avalanche Warning for the Centennial Mountains in Island Park, the Lionhead area near West Yellowstone, and the southern Madison and southern Gallatin ranges. New snow and wind are forming drifts and overloading an exceptionally weak snowpack, creating very dangerous avalanche conditions. Human- triggered and natural avalanches are likely. Avoid avalanche terrain and avalanche runout zones. The avalanche danger is HIGH on all slopes. Contact the Gallatin National Forest Avalanche Center for more detailed information.
Website: www.mtavalanche.com
Avalanche Hotline: 406-587-6981
This warning will expire or be updated by 6:00 a.m. on Wednesday, February 7th.
